<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project_specification>
  <project_name>causeflow-relay</project_name>
  <mode>existing-codebase</mode>

  <project_goal>
    Ship a hardened, read-only relay agent — packaged as a multi-arch Docker image (causeflowai/relay) and versioned via semantic-release — that connects outbound from a customer's private network to the CauseFlow control plane over a single WebSocket /v1/relay/connect endpoint, executes JSON-RPC 2.0 requests (execute, list_resources, describe_resource, health_check) against configured PostgreSQL and MongoDB resources, enforces per-resource policy (allowlist + row limits) and SQL/aggregation safety, masks PII before results leave the network, emits a structured JSON audit trail, and reports resource updates + a 30s heartbeat. The image runs as non-root UID 10001 with a read-only filesystem, all Linux capabilities dropped, and no inbound ports.
  </project_goal>

  <overview>
    CauseFlow Relay is a small Node.js 22 / TypeScript agent deployed inside the customer's VPC or on-prem environment. It opens an outbound WebSocket connection to the CauseFlow control plane at /v1/relay/connect, authenticates with a per-tenant token, and surfaces a JSON-RPC 2.0 interface that the CauseFlow AI investigation agents use to read from the customer's own databases. The relay never accepts inbound connections, never publishes a public IP, and never writes to the customer databases — it enforces read-only at three layers (the driver interface contract, the SQL/AST parser that blocks DDL/DML/dangerous functions, and a `BEGIN READ ONLY` PostgreSQL transaction with a 30-second statement timeout; for MongoDB, `$out` and `$merge` aggregation stages are blocked). Per-resource policy decides which databases are reachable, which operations each one permits (query, describe_table, list_tables, explain), and the maximum rows per query. PII masking (CPF, email, credit card, bearer token, BR phone, plus user-defined regexes) runs on every result row before anything leaves the customer's network, so the control plane and AI agents only ever see sanitized data. Every request is logged as a structured JSON audit entry. The image is published to Docker Hub as `causeflowai/relay` for `linux/amd64` and `linux/arm64`, with version tags derived from Conventional Commits via semantic-release.
  </overview>

  <technology_stack>
    <general>
      Node.js 22 ESM agent with a single TypeScript entry point (`src/index.ts`) that loads config, initializes drivers + engines, opens a WebSocket to the control plane, and handles JSON-RPC 2.0 messages. Single-package layout (no monorepo). Pinned via `node:22-alpine` in `Dockerfile` and `node-version: '22'` in every GitHub Actions workflow. Container-first distribution: a hardened multi-stage Docker image published to Docker Hub, with version tags computed by semantic-release. Conventional Commits enforced by commitlint on PRs; CI runs commitlint + `npm run build` + a Docker build smoke test; Release runs semantic-release followed by a multi-arch docker buildx build + push to `causeflowai/relay`.
    </general>
    <material_libraries>
      - Node.js 22 — runtime and Docker base image
      - TypeScript — source language; `tsc` (TypeScript Compiler) builds; `tsx` runs `npm run dev` (tsx watch on `src/index.ts`)
      - ws — WebSocket client used by `WsClient` (`src/transport/ws-client.ts`)
      - pg — PostgreSQL client with a connection pool (`src/drivers/postgres/pg-driver.ts`)
      - mongodb — MongoDB native driver used by `MongoDriver` (`src/drivers/mongodb/mongo-driver.ts`)
      - node-sql-parser — SQL AST parser used by `validateQuery` (`src/drivers/postgres/pg-query-parser.ts`)
      - zod — schema validation for the loaded config and every per-resource block (`src/config/schema.ts`)
      - pino — structured JSON logging across `src/index.ts`, per-driver loggers, `AuditLogger`, and the `WsClient`
      - uuid — generates the per-process `relayId` and per-request `requestId`
      - yaml — parses the `relay-config.yaml` file in `src/config/loader.ts`
      - semantic-release — versioning + changelog, configured in `release.config.js` and run in the release workflow
      - commitlint — Conventional Commits enforcement, configured in `commitlint.config.js` and run on PRs
